{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524428","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524428"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:04:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:04:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13993"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13993","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13993"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.17,0.29,0.11,0.38]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6627"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60265"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6627"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13993"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45687"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"560"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13450"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60265"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of a painless swelling on her right arm. She is a keen cyclist and first noticed the swelling after \u003Cs\u003Ea \u003C/s\u003Efalling from her bicycle when she hurt her right arm\u003Cs\u003E.\u003C/s\u003E Her medical history includes a right segmental mastectomy and axillary dissection for breast cancer four years ago. A specialist oncology review six months ago found no evidence of tumour recurrence. She takes tamoxifen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 4 cm smooth-surfaced, soft, mobile, non-tender swelling on the dorsum of her right forearm (Image). The overlying skin appears normal. There is no lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rupture of extensor digitorum","Chronic haematoma","Lymphoedema","Soft tissue sarcoma","Lipoma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a classic appearance of a subcutaneous lipoma - a soft, mobile, non-tender mass with normal overlying skin. While her history of breast cancer and trauma might raise concern for more serious pathology, the clinical features are most consistent with a benign process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELipoma\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common benign soft tissue tumour. They typically present as well-circumscribed, mobile masses in the subcutaneous tissue. They are usually asymptomatic and grow slowly. The smooth surface and mobility are characteristic features that help distinguish them from other masses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERupture of extensor digitorum\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with acute pain and functional deficit at the time of injury. There would likely be a palpable defect in the muscle belly rather than a smooth mass, and the patient would have weakness in finger extension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered given the history of trauma, but would typically show signs of resolving bruising and would be expected to gradually decrease in size over time rather than persist for three months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphoedema\u003C/strong\u003E can occur after axillary surgery but typically presents as diffuse swelling of the entire limb rather than a localised mass. Additionally, lymphoedema would be expected to involve the hand and be more prominent distally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESoft tissue sarcoma\u003C/strong\u003E is an important consideration given her history of breast cancer. However, sarcomas typically present as firm, fixed masses that grow progressively. The soft, mobile nature of this mass is more consistent with a benign lesion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lipomas are the most common benign soft tissue tumours, typically presenting as soft, mobile, non-tender subcutaneous masses.","Previous breast cancer and trauma history should raise concern for malignancy, but clinical features remain most consistent with benign pathology.","Key examination features of lipomas include smooth surface, mobility, and soft consistency."],"references":["Allen B, Rader C, Baigna A. Giant lipomas of the upper extremity. Can J Plast Surg 2007; 15:141-44."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45687"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13993"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20883"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20883"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/rJsYtw07rYidpbtIWgHZgNESfb7f9u.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/rJsYtw07rYidpbtIWgHZgNESfb7f9u.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45687","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45687"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-10T17:29:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-10T17:30:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6627"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60265"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"htt